        <productionVolumeComment xml:lang="en">The total soda ash, light production in 2005 is 7.81E10, based on production volumes in the solvay process. There are two main grades of soda ash, namely dense and light. Because there is no specification as to what pecentage of each type of soda ash is used as a neutralising agent, it is assumed that each of them contributes equally to the neutralising agent market for soda ash.
 
The major applications of soda ash as a neutralising agent are in water treatment and the pulp and paper industry. This is stated on a market research by Marianne Wesnæs and Bo Weidema, 2.-0 LCA consultants,( www.lca-net.com, 2006-10-19. URL: http://www.lca-net.com/files/naoh.pdf  Retrieved 13.02.2012)
Other industries where it is used as a neutralising agent is in soap manufacturing and in the food processing industry. In both it is used only partly as neutralising agent, and also for other purposes. (source: Rizwan Mailk (Carnation Exports), Pakistan, 2012; URL: http://rizwan36.en.ec21.com/Soda_Ash_Light--3320168_3320198.html)

The US geological survey indicates in 2005 that 10% of soda ash is used in soap &amp; detergents, 2% in pulp and paper and 1% in water treatment. Specific uses in the food industry are not indicated, therefore it is not accounted for. In the detergent and soap manufacturing, it is assumed that 10% of the total consumption is actually for neutralising purposes.

The production volume of sodium hydroxide equivalents is calculated based on the soda ash input.

This value is multiplied with the share of the GDP in Europe, 19.6% (2015-2019, World bank (2022): GDP, available here:  https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/NY.GDP.MKTP.PP.KD, accessed 17-05-2022.)</productionVolumeComment>
